clinicians during physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC8\u003C/strong\u003E is not a vertebra; it refers to the eighth cervical nerve, which exits between the C7 and T1 vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET1\u003C/strong\u003E is the first thoracic vertebra, located just below C7, and does not have as prominent a spinous process as C7.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC1\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the atlas, is the first cervical vertebra and supports the skull. It does not have a prominent spinous process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC6\u003C/strong\u003E is the sixth cervical vertebra, which is located above C7 and does not have as prominent a spinous process as C7.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vertebra prominens is the seventh cervical vertebra (C7), characterised by its prominent spinous process.","C7 is a key anatomical landmark for clinicians during physical examination of the spine."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59178"}},"question":{"data":{"ty